236
00:24:02,067 --> 00:24:06,446
Poles you pay wages.
Generally, they get a little more.

237
00:24:06,572 --> 00:24:09,116
- Are you listening?
- What was that about the SS?

238
00:24:09,241 --> 00:24:11,451
The rate? The what?

239
00:24:11,577 --> 00:24:14,788
The Jewish worker's salary,
you pay it directly to the SS, not to the worker.

240
00:24:14,830 --> 00:24:17,082
- He gets nothing.
- But it's less.

241
00:24:17,082 --> 00:24:19,334
- It's less than what I would pay a Pole.
- It's less?

242
00:24:19,376 --> 00:24:22,462
That's the point
I'm trying to make.

243
00:24:22,588 --> 00:24:25,132
Poles cost more.

244
00:24:25,883 --> 00:24:29,344
Why should I hire Poles?

245
00:24:29,511 --> 00:24:33,599
An enamelware factory,
over at, Lipowa Street.

246
00:24:33,599 --> 00:24:36,685
It, uh, it, um...
It's owned by a German.

247
00:24:36,727 --> 00:24:40,314
But it's outside the ghetto,
so you can barter for extra goods...

248
00:24:40,314 --> 00:24:42,107
...for eggs, I don't know
what you need...

249
00:24:42,149 --> 00:24:43,901
...with the Polish workers.
You can't get it here.

250
00:24:43,942 --> 00:24:47,613
Also, he's asking for ten
healthy women for the...

251
00:24:47,613 --> 00:24:49,323
I'm healthy!

252
00:24:49,948 --> 00:24:52,326
Bring your sister, okay?

253
00:24:58,707 --> 00:25:02,002
You need to convince them you have
a trade, something valuable to the war effort.

254
00:25:02,085 --> 00:25:04,463
- Like what?
-I'm a musician. - What if you don't?

255
00:25:04,546 --> 00:25:07,925
- Your name goes on a list.
- Your name is on the list, they put you on trucks...

256
00:25:08,008 --> 00:25:10,093
- No, no, no, that's not true.
- You're a musician?

257
00:25:10,177 --> 00:25:12,888
- Yeah.
- I'd find a good hiding place if I were you.

258
00:25:12,971 --> 00:25:17,768
- I'm not going to hide like some animal.
- There are places to hide.

259
00:25:22,564 --> 00:25:23,857
The next!

260
00:25:23,899 --> 00:25:27,653
I'm a graduate
of the University of Lwow.

261
00:25:27,736 --> 00:25:30,447
I used to work at the
hydroelectric station in Roznow...

262
00:25:30,531 --> 00:25:32,449
Blue card!

263
00:25:35,911 --> 00:25:39,957
I'm gonna get the necessary papers
because this card is no good any more.

264
00:25:40,040 --> 00:25:42,668
You can stay in this line all day,
you'll still get one of these.

265
00:25:42,751 --> 00:25:46,296
They are no good.
You'll have to leave the line now...

266
00:25:46,380 --> 00:25:50,968
...then you'll get a blue card, a Blauschein,
to say that you are an essential worker.

267
00:25:51,051 --> 00:25:54,304
I'll get these papers
for you at Pankiewicz.

268
00:25:54,429 --> 00:25:56,598
Pharmacist.
Just there, look!

269
00:25:56,598 --> 00:25:58,350
<i>Guess who is here?</i>

270
00:25:58,392 --> 00:26:01,186
Poldek!
Enjoying the weather, Poldek?

271
00:26:01,270 --> 00:26:03,897
- Enjoying the lines?
- Need some shoe polish?

272
00:26:03,939 --> 00:26:06,483
In metal container maybe!

273
00:26:06,942 --> 00:26:11,405
Not essential? I think you misunderstand
the meaning of the word.

274
00:26:11,405 --> 00:26:13,782
No blue card, sir.
Stand over there.

275
00:26:13,782 --> 00:26:16,618
Move. Next!

276
00:26:17,160 --> 00:26:19,580
What do you mean,
"Not essential"?

277
00:26:20,122 --> 00:26:25,878
I teach history and literature.
Since when it's not essential?

278
00:26:30,716 --> 00:26:33,135
He's metal polisher.

279
00:26:40,058 --> 00:26:42,644
- It was not right?
- It's very good. He's 53 years old.

280
00:26:42,686 --> 00:26:45,981
- It's too new.
-Thank you.

281
00:26:54,114 --> 00:26:56,617
You're crazy.
You left it in your drawer.

282
00:26:56,742 --> 00:26:58,535
How many times
have I told you?

283
00:26:58,535 --> 00:27:01,747
Your work certificate,
you keep in your pocket at all times.

284
00:27:01,830 --> 00:27:03,582
And you leave everything
in your drawer.

285
00:27:03,582 --> 00:27:06,293
How many times I've told you?

286
00:27:06,627 --> 00:27:10,047
I'm a metal polisher!

287
00:27:18,222 --> 00:27:21,266
<i>Take the round sheet of tin...</i>

288
00:27:21,308 --> 00:27:25,395
...dip it in soap emulsion.

289
00:27:25,395 --> 00:27:30,150
<i>Then place it centrally in the press.</i>

290
00:27:45,040 --> 00:27:48,752
We obtain the soup pot.
The soup pot!

291
00:27:48,877 --> 00:27:52,214
Soup pot!

292
00:27:52,297 --> 00:27:55,509
Grosz, Mrs Grosz, stay together.

293
00:27:59,179 --> 00:28:04,518
Look, sir, I have ten work permits here
for the German enamel factory...

294
00:28:04,518 --> 00:28:07,688
...and signed by Mr Bankier
and myself.

295
00:28:07,771 --> 00:28:12,609
<i>If it's carbonized,
clean it with a file.</i>

296
00:28:12,734 --> 00:28:17,239
But don't touch both the electrodes
at the same time.

297
00:28:17,239 --> 00:28:20,742
You'll get electrocuted.
Here, have a try.

298
00:28:24,663 --> 00:28:27,040
Roll the metal
under the press...

299
00:28:27,040 --> 00:28:29,626
...but be very careful
unless you want your fingers...

300
00:28:29,668 --> 00:28:32,921
...to become part of the teapot!

301
00:28:34,089 --> 00:28:37,801
- Occupation?
- I'm a writer. I play the flute.

302
00:28:37,843 --> 00:28:41,221
But Moses is a skilled metalworker.

303
00:28:41,221 --> 00:28:43,724
He can make tin pots.
He can make tanks.

304
00:28:43,807 --> 00:28:45,684
He can make whatever
Mr Schindler asks.

305
00:28:45,767 --> 00:28:48,437
He's highly skilled.
Give him your card.

306
00:28:48,437 --> 00:28:51,148
Moses, give him your card.

307
00:28:52,774 --> 00:28:58,280
<i>Now, dip the basin with the tongs
into the enamel solution.</i>

308
00:28:59,656 --> 00:29:04,870
<i>And after swiveling it around,
carefully place it aside to drip-dry.</i>

309
00:29:07,289 --> 00:29:11,251
And whatever he asks you, allow me
just to represent you and speak for you.

310
00:29:11,335 --> 00:29:13,128
Don't say a word!

311
00:29:13,212 --> 00:29:16,757
Filing, billing, keeping
track of my appointments, shorthand.

312
00:29:16,757 --> 00:29:20,844
- Typing, obviously. How is your typing?
- Uh, all right.

313
00:29:20,928 --> 00:29:22,930
Please!

314
00:30:15,941 --> 00:30:19,653
You need a secretary.
Pick one.

315
00:30:19,778 --> 00:30:24,658
I don't know how.
They're all so... qualified.

316
00:30:24,783 --> 00:30:27,661
You have to choose.

317
00:30:29,955 --> 00:30:32,749
Big smile, big smile!

318
00:30:53,812 --> 00:30:56,690
If you would,
look after my guest.

319
00:30:56,815 --> 00:31:01,695
Um, boxed teas are good.
Coffee, pât? um...

320
00:31:01,737 --> 00:31:05,657
...kielbasa sausage,
cheeses, Beluga caviar...

321
00:31:05,741 --> 00:31:07,784
...and, of course, who could live
without German cigarettes?

322
00:31:07,784 --> 00:31:10,370
Get me as many
as you can find.

323
00:31:10,495 --> 00:31:12,456
And some more fresh fruit.

324
00:31:12,539 --> 00:31:15,501
The real rarities,
oranges, lemons, pineapples.

325
00:31:15,584 --> 00:31:18,003
I need several boxes of Cuban cigars.
The best.

326
00:31:18,128 --> 00:31:19,338
And dark unsweetened chocolate...

327
00:31:19,379 --> 00:31:21,757
...not in the shape of ladyfingers,
the chunk chocolate.

328
00:31:21,798 --> 00:31:24,843
Big as my hand,
you sample at wine tastings.

329
00:31:24,885 --> 00:31:28,222
We're going to need lots of cognac.
The best, Hennessy.

330
00:31:28,305 --> 00:31:33,310
Dom Perignon champagne.
Um, get L 'espadon sardines...

331
00:31:33,352 --> 00:31:37,231
...and, oh,
try to find nylon stockings.

332
00:31:39,525 --> 00:31:42,778
<i>It is my distinct pleasure
to announce...</i>

333
00:31:42,861 --> 00:31:48,534
<i>...the fully operational status
of German enamel factory...</i>

334
00:31:49,243 --> 00:31:53,247
<i>...manufacturers of superior
enamelware crockery...</i>

335
00:31:53,455 --> 00:31:58,752
<i>...expressly designed
and crafted for military use.</i>

336
00:31:58,877 --> 00:32:01,547
<i>Utilizing only
the most modern equipment...</i>

337
00:32:01,630 --> 00:32:06,677
<i>...D.E.F.'s staff of highly skilled and
experienced artisans and journeymen...</i>

338
00:32:06,802 --> 00:32:10,305
<i>...deliver a product
of unparalleled quality...</i>

339
00:32:10,430 --> 00:32:14,351
<i>...enabling me to proffer,
with absolute confidence and pride...</i>

340
00:32:14,476 --> 00:32:17,020
<i>...a full line
of field and kitchenware...</i>

341
00:32:17,145 --> 00:32:21,191
<i>...unsurpassable in all respects
by my competitors.</i>

342
00:32:21,316 --> 00:32:24,528
See attached list
and available colours.

343
00:32:25,028 --> 00:32:28,782
Anticipating the enclosed bids
will meet with your approval...

344
00:32:28,782 --> 00:32:32,703
...looking forward to a long and
mutually prosperous association...

345
00:32:32,828 --> 00:32:35,914
...I extend to you in advance
my sincerest gratitude...

346
00:32:35,956 --> 00:32:39,042
...and very best regards.
Oskar Schindler.

347
00:32:39,168 --> 00:32:42,546
Yeah, I need 700 gross
from here for next Thursday.

348
00:32:42,671 --> 00:32:45,382
Nine hundred,
no, make it ten for Wednesday.

349
00:32:45,507 --> 00:32:50,429
All this stuff here goes to Madritsch's
factory on Tuesday of next week.

350
00:33:05,194 --> 00:33:08,572
My father was fond of saying,
"You need three things in life... "

351
00:33:08,697 --> 00:33:13,243
"... a good doctor,
a forgiving priest... "

352
00:33:13,285 --> 00:33:16,079
"... and a clever accountant. "

353
00:33:19,541 --> 00:33:23,504
The first two,
I've never had much use for.

354
00:33:23,670 --> 00:33:27,090
But the third!

355
00:33:32,387 --> 00:33:36,517
Just pretend, for Christ's sake!

356
00:33:39,770 --> 00:33:42,773
Is that all?

357
00:33:47,569 --> 00:33:50,781
I'm trying to thank you.

358
00:33:51,114 --> 00:33:55,035
I'm saying I couldn't
have done this without you.

359
00:33:57,579 --> 00:34:00,457
The usual thing would be
to acknowledge my gratitude.

360
00:34:00,582 --> 00:34:05,420
It would also, by the way,
be the courteous thing.

361
00:34:05,504 --> 00:34:08,257
You're welcome.

362
00:34:17,266 --> 00:34:19,685
Get out of here!

363
00:34:32,865 --> 00:34:36,076
<i>Klonowska, who is it?</i>

364
00:34:45,377 --> 00:34:48,547
She's so embarrassed.
Look at her.

365
00:35:00,100 --> 00:35:02,311
You know something?
You would like her.

366
00:35:02,394 --> 00:35:04,396
- Oskar, please!
- What?

367
00:35:04,479 --> 00:35:06,857
I don't have to like her...
just because you do.

368
00:35:06,982 --> 00:35:09,651
It doesn't work that way.

369
00:35:22,789 --> 00:35:25,375
You've done well here.

370
00:35:27,836 --> 00:35:30,380
You look wonderful.

371
00:35:33,175 --> 00:35:37,721
- Be careful of the step, miss.
- Mrs Schindler, Marek.

372
00:35:49,441 --> 00:35:54,112
- It's not a charade, all this?
- Charade? How could it be a charade?

373
00:35:54,196 --> 00:35:55,906
- The clothes, the car, the apartment.
- Wait a minute.

374
00:35:55,948 --> 00:35:59,159
Take a guess how many
people are on my payroll.

375
00:35:59,159 --> 00:36:00,410
Oskar!

376
00:36:00,452 --> 00:36:05,582
My father, at the height of his success,
had 50. I've got 350.

377
00:36:05,666 --> 00:36:10,254
350 workers on the factory floor,
with one purpose.

378
00:36:10,379 --> 00:36:12,381
To make pots and pans?

379
00:36:12,464 --> 00:36:16,343
To make money.
For me!

380
00:36:22,140 --> 00:36:26,270
Does anyone ask about me?

381
00:36:26,770 --> 00:36:33,068
Back home?
Everybody. All the time.

382
00:36:37,030 --> 00:36:42,870
They won't soon forget the name
Schindler here, I can tell you that.

383
00:36:43,495 --> 00:36:46,790
"Oskar Schindler"
they'll say.

384
00:36:46,832 --> 00:36:50,460
"Everybody remembers him. "

385
00:36:50,627 --> 00:36:54,756
"He did something extraordinary. "

386
00:36:55,340 --> 00:36:59,970
"He did something
no one else did. "

387
00:37:00,429 --> 00:37:06,226
"He came here with nothing,
a suitcase...

388
00:37:06,351 --> 00:37:12,399
"... and built a bankrupt
company into a major manufactory. "

389
00:37:12,524 --> 00:37:15,652
"And left with
a steamer trunk... "

390
00:37:15,736 --> 00:37:20,324
"... two steamer trunks
full of money. "

391
00:37:20,699 --> 00:37:24,578
"All the riches of the world. "

392
00:37:26,830 --> 00:37:30,209
It's comforting to see
that nothing's changed.

393
00:37:30,334 --> 00:37:33,670
You're wrong, Emilie.

394
00:37:34,254 --> 00:37:36,798
There's no way I could have
known this before but...

395
00:37:36,840 --> 00:37:39,676
...there was always
something missing.

396
00:37:39,843 --> 00:37:43,847
In every business I tried,
I can see now, it wasn't me that failed.

397
00:37:43,889 --> 00:37:46,683
Something was missing.

398
00:37:46,850 --> 00:37:50,354
Even if I'd known what it was,
there's nothing I could have done about it...

399
00:37:50,437 --> 00:37:55,025
...because you can't
create this thing.

400
00:37:55,150 --> 00:38:00,364
And it makes all the difference
in the world between success and failure.

401
00:38:01,240 --> 00:38:03,033
Luck?

402
00:38:05,494 --> 00:38:08,372
War!

403
00:38:31,854 --> 00:38:35,524
Should I stay?

404
00:38:36,191 --> 00:38:39,444
It's a beautiful city.

405
00:38:40,487 --> 00:38:44,700
I asked you if I should stay.

406
00:38:46,034 --> 00:38:48,495
It's up to you.

407
00:38:52,499 --> 00:38:57,087
Promise me, Oskar.
No doorman or maitre d' will ever presume...

408
00:38:57,171 --> 00:39:02,551
...I'm anyone other
than Mrs. Schindler, and I'll stay.

409
00:39:04,803 --> 00:39:07,014
Goodbye, darling.

410
00:39:23,655 --> 00:39:27,784
I could try to read this
or I could eat my lunch while it's still hot.

411
00:39:28,535 --> 00:39:29,745
We're doing well?

412
00:39:29,745 --> 00:39:31,163
- Yes.
- Better this month than last?

413
00:39:31,163 --> 00:39:33,457
- Yes.
- Any reason to think next month will be worse?

414
00:39:33,540 --> 00:39:36,335
The war could end.

415
00:39:46,845 --> 00:39:49,389
- What?
- There is a machinist outside...

416
00:39:49,389 --> 00:39:52,559
...who'd like to thank you
personally for giving him a job.

417
00:39:52,643 --> 00:39:57,814
Every day he comes. He's very grateful.
It'll just take a minute.

418
00:40:03,612 --> 00:40:06,073
Mr Lowenstein!

419
00:40:12,955 --> 00:40:16,083
I want to thank you, sir...

420
00:40:16,124 --> 00:40:18,836
...for giving me
the opportunity to work.

421
00:40:18,919 --> 00:40:21,880
You're welcome.
I'm sure you're doing a great job.

422
00:40:22,047 --> 00:40:26,301
The SS beat me up.
They would have killed me...

423
00:40:26,677 --> 00:40:31,056
...but I am essential
to the war effort, thanks to you.

424
00:40:31,139 --> 00:40:33,141
That's great.

425
00:40:33,225 --> 00:40:35,477
I work hard for you.

426
00:40:35,561 --> 00:40:39,940
- I'm sure you do.
- I'll continue to work hard for you.

427
00:40:39,982 --> 00:40:41,984
That's great. Thanks.

428
00:40:42,067 --> 00:40:44,444
- God bless you, sir.
- All right.

429
00:40:44,444 --> 00:40:48,282
You are a good man.

430
00:40:49,741 --> 00:40:52,786
- He saved my life.
- Yes, he did.

431
00:40:52,911 --> 00:40:56,415
- God bless him.
- Yeah. Come on.

432
00:40:57,749 --> 00:41:00,627
God bless you!

433
00:41:12,598 --> 00:41:15,267
I'm sorry, Herr Direktor,
but you're running very late.

434
00:41:15,350 --> 00:41:18,896
This is for the major, sir.

435
00:41:19,021 --> 00:41:21,940
And this is for his niece, Greta.
It's her birthday.

436
00:41:22,024 --> 00:41:24,735
- Greta as in Garbo.
- Don't ever do that to me again.

437
00:41:24,860 --> 00:41:27,404
Go. Go, go, drive!
Don't bow.

438
00:41:27,529 --> 00:41:31,450
- Did you notice that man had one arm?
- Did he?

439
00:41:35,162 --> 00:41:38,373
- What's his use?
- Very useful.

440
00:41:40,542 --> 00:41:44,338
- How?
- Very useful! Success!

441
00:42:12,783 --> 00:42:14,826
<i>You'll be given brooms and shovels...</i>

442
00:42:14,868 --> 00:42:17,913
<i>...each of you will grab one
and start cleaning the street.</i>

443
00:42:17,996 --> 00:42:20,999
We'll be late for work.

444
00:42:32,511 --> 00:42:35,556
You shouldn't
think of them as yours, Oskar.

445
00:42:35,681 --> 00:42:37,558
You need to understand that
some of the officers here...

446
00:42:37,599 --> 00:42:40,435
...don't give a damn
about production.

447
00:42:40,519 --> 00:42:44,606
To them, it's a matter of,
um, national priority...

448
00:42:44,690 --> 00:42:47,067
...that Jews
be made to shovel snow.

449
00:42:47,150 --> 00:42:49,611
<i>It's got nothing to do
with reality, Oskar.</i>

450
00:42:49,695 --> 00:42:51,780
<i>You know it and I know it.</i>

451
00:42:51,864 --> 00:42:54,074
<i>Jews shoveling snow!</i>

452
00:42:54,199 --> 00:42:58,912
<i>It's got a, um,
ritual significance.</i>

453
00:43:00,581 --> 00:43:04,001
- Come with me.
- I am an essential worker.

454
00:43:04,126 --> 00:43:06,795
- Essential worker?
- Yes.

455
00:43:09,715 --> 00:43:13,343
- I work for Oskar Schindler.
- Essential worker for Oskar Schindler.

456
00:43:13,385 --> 00:43:16,847
- A one-armed Jew? Twice as useless!
- Yes, yes.

457
00:43:17,472 --> 00:43:20,934
I lost a day
of production, Rolf.

458
00:43:21,059 --> 00:43:24,188
<i>I work for Oskar Schindler.</i>

459
00:43:24,730 --> 00:43:28,317
Danka, look at the snow.
Look at the snow. Look at the snow!

460
00:43:32,446 --> 00:43:36,200
I lost a worker.
I expect to be compensated.

461
00:43:36,325 --> 00:43:39,203
File a grievance with the
Economic Office. It's your right.

462
00:43:39,328 --> 00:43:42,998
- Would it do any good?
- Of course not!

463
00:43:45,000 --> 00:43:48,504
A big shot from the SS Budget
and Construction Office came to lunch...

464
00:43:48,545 --> 00:43:52,883
...and he told us that to believe
the Jewish skilled worker had a place...

465
00:43:53,008 --> 00:43:57,679
...in Reich economics
was a treasonable idea.

466
00:44:01,266 --> 00:44:05,896
A one-armed machinist, Oskar?

467
00:44:05,896 --> 00:44:08,941
He was a metal press operator.

468
