703
01:07:07,361 --> 01:07:11,907
No, get under the stairs. They'll be done
searching soon. You'll be safe there.

704
01:07:11,990 --> 01:07:15,369
- Please hide! Please!
- Warmed by the sun.

705
01:07:15,452 --> 01:07:17,871
Hide under the stairs!

706
01:07:20,457 --> 01:07:22,501
I've searched the building.
There's no one here.

707
01:07:22,584 --> 01:07:26,630
- Okay, then we're going to the next block.
-Understood!

708
01:07:33,512 --> 01:07:36,139
- Danka!
- Mama!

709
01:07:41,520 --> 01:07:43,730
Hello, Adam.

710
01:07:43,814 --> 01:07:45,983
Hello, Danka.

711
01:07:52,072 --> 01:07:55,909
Come with me.
I will put you in the good line.

712
01:07:57,744 --> 01:08:00,914
Do you know the saying,
"An hour of life is still life"?

713
01:08:00,998 --> 01:08:05,252
You are not a boy any more.
I'm saying a blessing for you.

714
01:09:42,349 --> 01:09:45,769
Oh, please, let's go.
Let's go, please!

715
01:09:46,186 --> 01:09:47,938
Come on!

716
01:10:56,798 --> 01:10:58,800
Mark it...

717
01:10:58,884 --> 01:11:00,928
...mark it!

718
01:12:27,764 --> 01:12:31,852
- What is it? Is it Bach?
- No, no. It's Mozart.

719
01:12:31,935 --> 01:12:33,979
- Mozart?
- Yes!

720
01:12:53,707 --> 01:12:57,211
- Can we still manage today?
- No way!

721
01:13:01,840 --> 01:13:03,967
We can't manage it.

722
01:13:04,092 --> 01:13:07,554
I wish this fucking
night were over.

723
01:13:45,008 --> 01:13:49,221
<i>Appeal!
Line up! In rows of five!</i>

724
01:13:49,304 --> 01:13:52,099
<i>Line up!</i>

725
01:13:53,725 --> 01:13:56,687
<i>Line up!</i>

726
01:13:58,564 --> 01:14:01,733
<i>Come on, in rows of five!</i>

727
01:14:01,817 --> 01:14:04,152
Caps off!

728
01:14:06,071 --> 01:14:07,573
Sort the names!

729
01:14:07,573 --> 01:14:11,326
Those who're announced will raise
their hands and shout a clear "Yes"!

730
01:14:12,160 --> 01:14:14,121
<i>Yes!</i>

731
01:14:16,707 --> 01:14:17,791
<i>Yes!</i>

732
01:14:17,833 --> 01:14:21,128
- Keller, Fanni!
- Yes!

733
01:14:21,211 --> 01:14:25,674
- Adalbert, Hermann!
- Yes!

734
01:14:25,757 --> 01:14:28,135
- Faber, Dorothea!
- Yes!

735
01:14:28,218 --> 01:14:31,638
- Goldstein, Pola!
- Yes!

736
01:14:31,722 --> 01:14:35,142
-Warmberger, Markus!
-Yes!

737
01:14:36,476 --> 01:14:39,313
Edelstein, Max!

738
01:14:57,164 --> 01:14:59,833
Disband!

739
01:15:02,002 --> 01:15:05,547
The worst is over.
We are workers now.

740
01:15:36,620 --> 01:15:39,790
<i>No excuses!</i>

741
01:15:44,044 --> 01:15:47,714
Oh, God, Amon!

742
01:15:51,635 --> 01:15:56,640
<i>Go to your barracks immediately!</i>

743
01:16:38,682 --> 01:16:41,602
<i>Come here, come here!</i>

744
01:16:41,685 --> 01:16:44,104
<i>Come on, come here!</i>

745
01:16:46,857 --> 01:16:50,068
Amon, you're
such a damned fuckin' child!

746
01:16:50,110 --> 01:16:52,613
Wakey, wakey.

747
01:17:02,372 --> 01:17:05,876
- Make coffee.
- Make it yourself.

748
01:17:20,849 --> 01:17:25,437
<i>The SS will manage
certain industries itself inside Plaszow.</i>

749
01:17:25,479 --> 01:17:27,898
<i>A metalworks, brush factory...</i>

750
01:17:27,981 --> 01:17:31,151
<i>...another for reprocessing
jewish clothing from the ghettos...</i>

751
01:17:31,235 --> 01:17:33,779
<i>...for use by
bombed-out families back home.</i>

752
01:17:33,862 --> 01:17:37,199
But it's private industry like yours
that stands to benefit most...

753
01:17:37,282 --> 01:17:39,993
...by moving inside the wire of
Commandant Amon Goeth's camp...

754
01:17:40,077 --> 01:17:42,621
No, no, no. Sit, sit.
Julian, how are you?

755
01:17:42,704 --> 01:17:44,164
Good to see you, my friend.

756
01:17:44,206 --> 01:17:47,251
- Oskar Schindler.
- Leo John.

757
01:17:50,796 --> 01:17:53,757
- Franz, good to see you.
- Hello, Oskar. Glad you could join us.

758
01:17:53,841 --> 01:17:57,427
- My pleasure. Julius.
- How are you? You lost weight.

759
01:17:57,511 --> 01:18:01,390
Only in the shoulders.
Please, everybody, sit down.

760
01:18:01,473 --> 01:18:04,142
How are you doing?
Oskar Schindler.

761
01:18:05,853 --> 01:18:09,273
- We started without you.
- Fine. I miss anything good?

762
01:18:09,773 --> 01:18:12,609
I was explaining to Herr Bosch
and Herr Madritsch...

763
01:18:12,693 --> 01:18:15,529
...some of the benefits of moving
their factories into Plaszow.

764
01:18:15,612 --> 01:18:18,240
I meant the food.

765
01:18:20,450 --> 01:18:24,329
Since your labour is housed on-site,
it's available to you at all times.

766
01:18:24,413 --> 01:18:27,082
You can work them
all night if you want.

767
01:18:27,165 --> 01:18:31,628
Your factory policies, whatever they've
been in the past, they'll continue to be.

768
01:18:31,712 --> 01:18:33,839
They'll be respected.

769
01:18:33,922 --> 01:18:38,177
I have to know, where do you get a suit
like that? What is that? Is that silk?

770
01:18:38,260 --> 01:18:40,220
Of course!

771
01:18:40,304 --> 01:18:44,600
Yeah, it's, it has a nice sheen
about it.

772
01:18:44,683 --> 01:18:46,560
- Thank you.
- Very nice.

773
01:18:46,643 --> 01:18:50,397
I'd say I'd get you one, but the man
who made it is probably dead.

774
01:18:50,480 --> 01:18:53,066
I don't know.

775
01:18:53,150 --> 01:18:56,820
<i>I go to work the other day.</i>

776
01:18:56,904 --> 01:18:58,989
<i>Nobody's there.</i>

777
01:18:59,072 --> 01:19:02,743
<i>Nobody tells me about this.
I have to find out. I have to go in.</i>

778
01:19:03,744 --> 01:19:06,413
<i>Everybody's gone.</i>

779
01:19:06,496 --> 01:19:08,582
No!

780
01:19:09,499 --> 01:19:11,585
No!

781
01:19:14,338 --> 01:19:16,840
They're not gone.
They're here.

782
01:19:16,924 --> 01:19:22,012
They're mine!
Every day that goes by, I'm losing money.

783
01:19:22,095 --> 01:19:24,932
Every worker that is shot costs me money.
I have to find somebody else.

784
01:19:24,932 --> 01:19:25,807
I have to trade them!

785
01:19:25,849 --> 01:19:28,977
We are going to be making so much
money that none of this is going to matter.

786
01:19:29,019 --> 01:19:32,523
It's bad business.

787
01:19:43,408 --> 01:19:45,369
Thank you.

788
01:19:45,452 --> 01:19:47,996
Leave the bottle.

789
01:19:49,248 --> 01:19:51,458
Take that.

790
01:19:51,542 --> 01:19:55,170
Lena, thank you.

791
01:20:04,304 --> 01:20:07,891
Scherner told me
something else about you.

792
01:20:09,643 --> 01:20:12,104
Yeah? What's that?

793
01:20:12,187 --> 01:20:16,942
That you know the meaning
of the word "gratitude. "

794
01:20:17,150 --> 01:20:20,445
That it's not some vague thing with you...

795
01:20:20,529 --> 01:20:23,782
...like it is with others.

796
01:20:23,866 --> 01:20:27,327
You want to stay where you are.

797
01:20:27,411 --> 01:20:30,539
You've got things
going on the side.

798
01:20:30,622 --> 01:20:32,708
Things are good.

799
01:20:32,791 --> 01:20:37,337
You don't want anybody
telling you what to do.

800
01:20:37,421 --> 01:20:41,884
I can understand all that,
you know? I know you.

801
01:20:43,969 --> 01:20:49,266
What you want...
is your own sub-camp.

802
01:20:54,646 --> 01:20:57,983
Do you have any idea what is involved?
The paperwork alone?

803
01:20:58,025 --> 01:21:02,571
You've got to build the fucking thing. Getting
the fucking permits is enough to drive you crazy.

804
01:21:02,613 --> 01:21:06,366
Then the engineers show up, they stand
around, they argue about drainage, foundations...

805
01:21:06,408 --> 01:21:11,830
...codes, exact specifications, fences 4
kilometres long, 1,200 kilograms of barbed wire...

806
01:21:11,914 --> 01:21:15,167
...6,000 kilograms of electrified
fences, ceramic insulators...

807
01:21:15,250 --> 01:21:16,835
...three cubic metres
of air space per prisoner.

808
01:21:16,877 --> 01:21:21,089
I'm telling you, you want to shoot
somebody. I've been through it. I know.

809
01:21:21,173 --> 01:21:24,927
Well, you know.
You've been through it.

810
01:21:27,012 --> 01:21:30,140
You could make things
easier for me.

811
01:21:33,101 --> 01:21:35,103
I'd be grateful.

812
01:21:38,982 --> 01:21:40,984
<i>Clear the road!</i>

813
01:21:50,827 --> 01:21:55,040
<i>Keep moving!
Keep moving!</i>

814
01:22:01,171 --> 01:22:04,007
<i>-Keep moving!
-Turn left!</i>

815
01:22:10,347 --> 01:22:12,933
Where's Stern?

816
01:22:15,978 --> 01:22:20,148
Goldberg and Chilowicz,
make sure I see my cut...

817
01:22:20,232 --> 01:22:23,735
...from the, uh,
factory owners in this camp...

818
01:22:23,819 --> 01:22:27,155
...leaving you to take care
of my main account...

819
01:22:27,239 --> 01:22:30,534
...the Schindler account.

820
01:22:30,617 --> 01:22:34,746
He wants his independence.
I gave it to him.

821
01:22:34,830 --> 01:22:37,749
But independence costs money.

822
01:22:37,833 --> 01:22:40,669
This you understand?

823
01:22:45,090 --> 01:22:47,092
Look at me!

824
01:22:57,728 --> 01:23:01,899
Don't forget
who you are working for now.

825
01:23:10,490 --> 01:23:14,494
<i>- Yes!
- Make sure he stays. He's a slippery bastard!</i>

826
01:23:15,120 --> 01:23:18,332
<i>Yes!
Now, girls, everyone.</i>

827
01:23:21,168 --> 01:23:23,837
- We need more wine.
- More wine!

828
01:23:23,921 --> 01:23:27,466
<i>Stand on my friend.
Don't let him leave.</i>

829
01:23:43,565 --> 01:23:47,027
- What happens in life...
-Cheers, cheers!

830
01:23:49,947 --> 01:23:52,032
Thank you, Mr. Director.

831
01:23:52,074 --> 01:23:54,117
Cheers, Mr. Director!

832
01:23:58,288 --> 01:24:01,750
- What are you doing?
- What? Scratching my head.

833
01:24:01,834 --> 01:24:06,296
Makes them think we have lice.
Helps make them keep their distance.

834
01:24:06,380 --> 01:24:08,882
- Do you have lice?
- Do you have your notebook?

835
01:24:08,966 --> 01:24:12,594
The calendar on my desk has the birthdays
of our SS friends' wives and children.

836
01:24:12,678 --> 01:24:15,013
Don't forget to send something.

837
01:24:15,097 --> 01:24:18,642
Record pay-offs to the Main Administration
and Economics Office, the Armaments...

838
01:24:18,767 --> 01:24:21,186
- Slowly, Stern, slowly.
- The Armaments Board...

839
01:24:21,270 --> 01:24:25,732
...Governor General's Division of the
Interior and Chief of Police as "fees"...

840
01:24:25,816 --> 01:24:27,901
...and make them
on the first of each month...

841
01:24:27,985 --> 01:24:30,404
...as opposed to individual pay-offs
to our SS contacts.

842
01:24:30,487 --> 01:24:32,531
The list is
in the lower drawer of my desk...

843
01:24:32,531 --> 01:24:35,659
-... which you...
-"First of month... "

844
01:24:35,826 --> 01:24:38,412
SS contacts: List, lower drawer
of my desk, which you handle...

845
01:24:38,537 --> 01:24:42,875
...as cash contributions to legitimate
charities sent to each official's office.

846
01:24:42,958 --> 01:24:46,378
Dealings with our black market contacts,
listed as suppliers...

847
01:24:46,461 --> 01:24:49,423
-... in the legitimate ledger, are more complicated.
- Forget it!

848
01:24:49,506 --> 01:24:53,927
- What do you mean, you can't forget it!
- It gives me a headache!

849
01:25:00,601 --> 01:25:04,062
- I couldn't get you out of here.
- I'll be all right.

850
01:25:04,146 --> 01:25:08,483
Anyway, I'm here almost every week.
Wednesdays, usually.

851
01:25:08,567 --> 01:25:12,154
I'll look in on you,
see how you're doing.

852
01:25:13,488 --> 01:25:17,576
Here,
put these in your pocket.

853
01:25:17,659 --> 01:25:19,703
Come on!

854
01:25:23,540 --> 01:25:28,212
Mr. Director, don't let things fall apart.
I've worked too hard.

855
01:25:36,512 --> 01:25:41,183
Thanks for...
Good luck!

856
01:26:02,412 --> 01:26:05,415
Attention! Caps off!

857
01:26:15,008 --> 01:26:18,136
-Work!
-Back to work!

858
01:26:31,733 --> 01:26:36,363
-What are you making?
-Hinges, sir!

859
01:26:38,615 --> 01:26:42,244
Yeah, I've got some workers coming in
tomorrow. Where are they from again?

860
01:26:42,327 --> 01:26:44,413
Yugoslavia, Mr. Commander!

861
01:26:44,496 --> 01:26:47,040
I've got to make room.

862
01:26:49,501 --> 01:26:52,963
- Make me a hinge.
- Yes, sir!

863
01:27:24,203 --> 01:27:27,414
Keep going, you're doing well.

864
01:27:27,497 --> 01:27:29,583
Says he's doing well.

865
01:27:36,256 --> 01:27:38,926
Oh, that's very good.

866
01:27:39,009 --> 01:27:42,763
But I'm a bit confused,
and perhaps you can help me.

867
01:27:42,846 --> 01:27:46,475
What I don't understand
is that you've been working...

868
01:27:46,558 --> 01:27:51,104
.. since I think, what,
about 6.00 this morning?

869
01:27:51,647 --> 01:27:56,276
Yet such a small pile of hinges.

870
01:28:25,389 --> 01:28:28,392
- Oh, Christ.
- May I try that, sir?

871
01:28:28,475 --> 01:28:30,644
Check the angle lever.
Maybe it's bent.

872
01:28:30,727 --> 01:28:34,064
No, no. You wouldn't hear a click
if it was the angle lever.

873
01:28:34,147 --> 01:28:36,650
- Maybe the pin shaft is greasy.
- Yeah, come on.

874
01:28:36,733 --> 01:28:39,903
What did I just say?
Here.

875
01:28:42,698 --> 01:28:43,991
Mr. Commander!

876
01:28:44,032 --> 01:28:49,580
I beg to report that my heap
of hinges was so unsatisfactory...

877
01:28:49,621 --> 01:28:53,667
...because the machines
were being recalibrated this morning.

878
01:28:55,419 --> 01:28:58,589
I was put on to shoveling coal.

879
01:29:22,446 --> 01:29:24,531
Strange, huh?

880
01:29:24,615 --> 01:29:26,575
Yeah!

881
01:29:31,246 --> 01:29:34,541
Thank you, Muek.

882
01:29:34,625 --> 01:29:38,337
Ah, Lisiek. Don't touch the leather,
it's just been oiled.

883
01:29:38,420 --> 01:29:40,297
- Squad leader!
- Oh, for me?

884
01:29:40,339 --> 01:29:44,092
-Oh, thank you very much, Mr Director.
-Mr. Director!

885
01:29:44,176 --> 01:29:46,720
Mr. Director!

886
01:29:49,181 --> 01:29:51,850
Mr. Director!

887
01:29:53,727 --> 01:29:54,895
<i>He was making hinges slowly.</i>

888
01:29:54,937 --> 01:30:00,192
So the man can turn out a hinge in
less than a minute. Why the long story?

889
01:30:28,971 --> 01:30:32,015
- Thank you, sir.
- You're welcome!

890
01:30:35,185 --> 01:30:39,064
- Nobody knows who stole the chicken?
- Tell him about the chicken.

891
01:30:39,147 --> 01:30:43,944
A man walks around with a chicken
and nobody notices this.

892
01:30:44,027 --> 01:30:46,613
Save yourselves.

893
01:30:46,697 --> 01:30:49,116
<i>Tell him about the chicken.</i>

894
01:31:04,715 --> 01:31:06,884
Still nobody knows?

895
01:31:18,520 --> 01:31:22,316
It was you!
You committed this crime!

896
01:31:22,399 --> 01:31:24,818
- No, sir.
- But you know who, though.

897
01:31:24,902 --> 01:31:27,154
- Yes.
- Who?

898
01:31:28,197 --> 01:31:30,282
Him!

899
01:31:33,744 --> 01:31:37,664
- He's very gifted.
- Yeah, sure. Bring him over.

900
01:31:40,459 --> 01:31:44,338
Sir, thank you.

901
01:31:50,469 --> 01:31:53,263
- Thank you again, Mr. Director!
- You're welcome again.

902
01:31:53,347 --> 01:31:55,849
It's an honour to work
for such a great company.

903
01:31:55,849 --> 01:31:56,892
It's great to have you!

904
01:31:56,975 --> 01:32:00,604
I promise to learn everything there's
to know about enamelware production.

905
01:32:00,604 --> 01:32:02,189
That's great!

906
01:32:13,742 --> 01:32:18,121
- Hello? Miss Elsa Krause is here.
- I only need five minutes.

907
01:32:18,205 --> 01:32:20,916
She wants to speak
to Mr. Director.

908
01:32:40,435 --> 01:32:42,646
Yes.

909
01:32:46,900 --> 01:32:49,695
He won't see you.

910
01:33:19,766 --> 01:33:21,935
Please, sit down.

911
01:33:25,022 --> 01:33:28,275
- Pernod? Cognac?
- Uh, no. No, thank you.

912
01:33:29,193 --> 01:33:32,738
So, what can I do for you?

913
01:33:36,783 --> 01:33:39,328
They say that no one dies here.

914
01:33:39,411 --> 01:33:42,998
They say your factory is a haven.

915
01:33:44,499 --> 01:33:46,960
They say you are good.

916
01:33:49,963 --> 01:33:52,174
Who says that?

917
01:33:52,257 --> 01:33:54,426
Everyone.

918
01:34:00,724 --> 01:34:03,227
My name is Regina Perlman,
not Elsa Krause.

919
01:34:03,310 --> 01:34:06,897
I've been living in Krakow
on false papers since the ghetto massacre.

920
01:34:06,980 --> 01:34:08,565
My parents are in Plaszow.

921
01:34:08,649 --> 01:34:13,153
Their names are
Chana and Jakob Perlman.

922
01:34:13,237 --> 01:34:16,907
They are older people. They are killing
older people now in Plaszow.

923
01:34:16,949 --> 01:34:21,286
They bury them
up in the forest. Look...

924
01:34:21,370 --> 01:34:24,081
...I don't have any money.

925
01:34:24,164 --> 01:34:27,626
I, I borrowed these clothes.

926
01:34:29,753 --> 01:34:31,839
I'm begging you.

927
01:34:31,922 --> 01:34:35,759
Please, please
bring them here.

928
01:34:35,843 --> 01:34:38,345
I don't do that.

929
01:34:38,428 --> 01:34:42,140
You've been misled.
I ask one thing:

930
01:34:42,224 --> 01:34:45,727
Whether or not a worker
has certain skills.

931
01:34:45,811 --> 01:34:48,313
My father is an importer,
not a metalworker.

932
01:34:48,355 --> 01:34:52,901
Such activities are illegal.
You will not entrap me!

933
01:34:52,985 --> 01:34:57,114
Cry, and I will have you arrested.
I swear to God!

934
01:35:06,707 --> 01:35:09,459
People die.
It's a fact of life.

935
01:35:09,543 --> 01:35:13,172
He wants to kill everybody? Great!
What am I supposed to do about it?

936
01:35:13,255 --> 01:35:16,008
Bring everybody over?
Is that what you think?

937
01:35:16,091 --> 01:35:19,052
Send them over to Schindler.
Send them all!

938
01:35:19,136 --> 01:35:22,890
